('economics:3-2-low-unemployment:exam:bd0ee6af', 'economics', 'economics:3-2-low-unemployment', '3.2 Low Unemployment', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q2", "question": "The graph shows that following the Financial Crisis in 2007/8 jobs were cut across the EU. According to the graph, the unemployment rate", "options": ["peaked in 2009", "rose most sharply between 2008 and 2009", "was higher at the beginning of the period than at the end", "was never less than 8 %"], "caseStudy": "<img src=\"/images/economics/3-2-eu-unemployment-chart-extracted.png\" alt=\"Line chart from the OCR exam paper titled ''EU Unemployment Rate (%) 2005-2014'': about 9.0% in 2005, 8.2% in 2006, 7.2% in 2007, 7.0% in 2008, rising sharply to 9.0% in 2009, then 9.6% in 2010, 9.7% in 2011, 10.5% in 2012, a peak of 10.9% in 2013 and 10.2% in 2014\" style=\"display:block;width:100%;max-width:520px;margin:14px auto;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:8px;background:#fff;padding:6px;\" />", "hint": "Look for the STEEPEST climb between two consecutive years, then check each of the other statements against the chart.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO2)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: B — rose most sharply between 2008 and 2009</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>The rate jumps from about 7.0% to 9.0% — a 2-point rise, the steepest on the chart. It peaked in 2013 (≈10.9%), not 2009; it was LOWER at the start (9.0%) than the end (10.2%); and it fell to about 7.0% in 2008, so it was not always ≥8%.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-2-low-unemployment:exam:228f4411', 'economics', 'economics:3-2-low-unemployment', '3.2 Low Unemployment', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q3", "question": "Which one of the following is most likely to reduce unemployment?", "options": ["Increased government expenditure", "Increased imports", "Increased interest rates", "Increased taxes"], "hint": "Which option RAISES demand in the economy, so firms need more workers? The other three all reduce demand for UK output.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO1b)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: A — Increased government expenditure</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>More government spending raises total demand, so firms produce more and hire more workers. Higher imports, interest rates and taxes all reduce demand for domestic output and tend to raise unemployment.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-2-low-unemployment:exam:af77feb2', 'economics', 'economics:3-2-low-unemployment', '3.2 Low Unemployment', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q4", "question": "The claimant count:", "options": ["cannot be used to measure the rate of unemployment", "includes people receiving jobseeker''s allowance", "measures the different causes of unemployment", "uses the CPI to measure the level of unemployment"], "hint": "The claimant count counts people CLAIMING unemployment-related benefits. What benefit is that?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO1a)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: B — includes people receiving jobseeker''s allowance</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>The claimant count measures unemployment by counting those claiming JSA. The CPI measures inflation, not unemployment.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Examiner''s Comments</h5>\n<p>A significant proportion of candidates identified the correct answer (B).</p>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-2-low-unemployment:exam:1773ca0e', 'economics', 'economics:3-2-low-unemployment', '3.2 Low Unemployment', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q5", "question": "What is the most likely cause of structural unemployment?", "options": ["Different jobs are available in the summer", "High levels of occupational immobility", "Increased migration into the country", "The closure of some discount food stores"], "hint": "Structural unemployment is about a MISMATCH between workers'' skills and the jobs available. Which option describes workers unable to move between occupations?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO1b)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: B — High levels of occupational immobility</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Structural unemployment arises when an industry declines and workers'' skills no longer match the vacancies — occupational immobility. Seasonal work (A) causes SEASONAL unemployment.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Examiner''s Comments</h5>\n<p>A relatively common misconception was candidates selecting answer ''D'', rather than ''B''.</p>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-2-low-unemployment:exam:c6f8fd44', 'economics', 'economics:3-2-low-unemployment', '3.2 Low Unemployment', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q6", "question": "What is NOT a cost of unemployment for individuals?", "options": ["Loss of self-esteem", "Lower standard of living", "Higher direct taxes", "Waste of labour resources"], "hint": "Three of these are felt by a PERSON. One is a cost to the whole economy/society rather than to an individual.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO1b)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: D — Waste of labour resources</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Wasted labour is a cost to the ECONOMY as a whole, not to an individual. Loss of self-esteem, a lower standard of living and higher taxes are all borne by individuals.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Examiner''s Comments</h5>\n<p>There was a wider spread of answers here, indicating that candidates may not have fully understood that the question was about finding the answer that impacted the whole of society/the economy, rather than the individual.</p>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-2-low-unemployment:exam:91125e88', 'economics', 'economics:3-2-low-unemployment', '3.2 Low Unemployment', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q8", "question": "The claimant count measure of unemployment will include", "options": ["all individuals receiving jobseeker''s allowance", "all individuals who are looking for a job", "all individuals without a job", "only individuals able to start work immediately"], "hint": "The clue is in the name — it counts people CLAIMING a benefit, not everyone who is jobless or job-hunting.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO1a)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: A — all individuals receiving jobseeker''s allowance</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>The claimant count only counts those actually claiming JSA. Many people looking for work do not claim, and people without a job may not be seeking one — so B and C are wider than the claimant count.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Examiner''s Comments</h5>\n<p>A significant proportion of candidates answered correctly, although a common misconception was B and C.</p>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-2-low-unemployment:exam:8c8c01ed', 'economics', 'economics:3-2-low-unemployment', '3.2 Low Unemployment', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q9", "question": "What is most likely to cause frictional unemployment?", "options": ["A delay in workers being able to start new jobs", "A high level of occupational mobility", "A permanent decline in one sector of industry", "Fewer jobs are available in the winter"], "hint": "Frictional unemployment is the short gap BETWEEN jobs. Which option describes a time lag?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO1b)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: A — A delay in workers being able to start new jobs</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Frictional unemployment is caused by time lags as workers move between jobs. A permanent decline in a sector (C) is STRUCTURAL; fewer winter jobs (D) is SEASONAL.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Examiner''s Comments</h5>\n<p>A significant proportion of candidates correctly answered A.</p>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-2-low-unemployment:exam:0dc743a0', 'economics', 'economics:3-2-low-unemployment', '3.2 Low Unemployment', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q10", "question": "What may NOT be a cost of unemployment for a government?", "options": ["A budget deficit", "A decrease in revenue from VAT", "A higher level of crime", "A lower rate of inflation"], "hint": "Three of these are problems for the government. One is something governments actually WANT.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO1b)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: D — A lower rate of inflation</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Lower inflation is a government OBJECTIVE, not a cost. A budget deficit, falling VAT revenue and higher crime are all genuine costs of unemployment to the government.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Examiner''s Comments</h5>\n<p>A significant proportion of candidates correctly answered D.</p>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-2-low-unemployment:exam:0101798c', 'economics', 'economics:3-2-low-unemployment', '3.2 Low Unemployment', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q11", "question": "What was the country''s unemployment rate if 2.52 million people were unemployed in 2022?", "options": ["4.8%", "5.7%", "6.3%", "8.0%"], "caseStudy": "<p>In 2022 a country''s population was 52.5 million. 8.5 million were under the age of 18 and the workforce was 31.5 million.</p>", "hint": "The unemployment rate uses the WORKFORCE as the denominator — not the population, and not the over-18s. Which figure is the workforce?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark · Quantitative skills</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: D — 8.0%</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Unemployment rate = unemployed ÷ workforce × 100 = 2.52m ÷ 31.5m × 100 = 8.0%. The 52.5m population and the 8.5m under-18s are distractors — the rate is always a share of the WORKFORCE.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Examiner''s Comments</h5>\n<p>A significant proportion of candidates correctly answered D.</p>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-2-low-unemployment:exam:3d6cb3fd', 'economics', 'economics:3-2-low-unemployment', '3.2 Low Unemployment', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q14", "question": "This type of unemployment is", "options": ["cyclical", "frictional", "seasonal", "structural"], "caseStudy": "<p>Jane lives in a UK seaside holiday resort. When the resort is busy, she works selling ice creams on the seafront. The rest of the year she is unemployed.</p>", "hint": "Her work depends on the time of year — the resort is only busy in summer.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: C — seasonal</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Jane is out of work because demand for ice cream falls outside the holiday season — seasonal unemployment, caused by a fall in demand during a particular season.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-2-low-unemployment:exam:78c53716', 'economics', 'economics:3-2-low-unemployment', '3.2 Low Unemployment', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q15", "question": "The claimant count is a method of measuring", "options": ["distribution of income", "economic growth", "inflation", "unemployment"], "hint": "Who are the ''claimants''? What are they claiming, and what does counting them tell you?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: D — unemployment</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>The claimant count measures unemployment by counting those claiming unemployment-related benefits. Inflation is measured by the CPI.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-2-low-unemployment:exam:67c0adf3', 'economics', 'economics:3-2-low-unemployment', '3.2 Low Unemployment', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q16", "question": "The diagram shows the female unemployment rates in Italy and the UK. Which of the following statements MUST be true?", "options": ["Fewer females were unemployed in the UK in 2019 than in 2006", "More females were unemployed in Italy than in the UK between 2006 and 2019", "The UK''s female unemployment rate is always higher than Italy''s", "The UK''s labour market for females has performed better than Italy''s"], "caseStudy": "<img src=\"/images/economics/3-2-italy-uk-female-unemployment-extracted.png\" alt=\"Line chart from the OCR exam paper titled ''Female Unemployment Rates (%) for the United Kingdom and Italy 2006-2019'': Italy (dashed line) starts around 8.8% in 2006, dips slightly, then rises to a peak of about 13.5% around 2013-2014 before easing to about 10.5% by 2019; the United Kingdom (solid line) starts around 5%, peaks at about 7.5% around 2011-2012, then falls steadily to about 3.5% by 2019\" style=\"display:block;width:100%;max-width:520px;margin:14px auto;border:1px solid var(--border);border-radius:8px;background:#fff;padding:6px;\" />", "hint": "''MUST be true'' — the chart shows RATES, not numbers of people, so anything about how MANY women were unemployed needs population data you don''t have.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: D — The UK''s labour market for females has performed better than Italy''s</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>The UK''s rate is below Italy''s throughout and ends lower than it started, so its labour market clearly performed better. A and B talk about the NUMBER of women unemployed, which a rate chart cannot tell you without population data. C is the wrong way round — the UK''s rate is always LOWER.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-2-low-unemployment:exam:15fb80c2', 'economics', 'economics:3-2-low-unemployment', '3.2 Low Unemployment', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q17", "question": "Which of the following would be classified as being unemployed?", "options": ["A father who chooses to stay at home to look after a child", "A full-time student who sometimes works in a café", "A pensioner who is looking for part-time work", "A young adult who has just left university without a job"], "hint": "To be unemployed you must be of working age, WITHOUT work, and actively seeking it. Check each option against all three tests.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: D — A young adult who has just left university without a job</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>They are of working age, without work and seeking it. The stay-at-home father is economically inactive by choice, the student already has some work, and a pensioner is beyond working age — none is counted as unemployed.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-2-low-unemployment:exam:6f2b94b2', 'economics', 'economics:3-2-low-unemployment', '3.2 Low Unemployment', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q18", "question": "The kind of unemployment he experienced was", "options": ["cyclical", "frictional", "seasonal", "structural"], "caseStudy": "<p>Dylan''s job in the Welsh coalmine came to an end when the pit was closed.</p>", "hint": "The pit closed permanently — the industry itself has declined, leaving his mining skills mismatched to available jobs.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: D — structural</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>A permanent decline in an industry (coal mining) leaves workers whose skills no longer match the vacancies available — the definition of structural unemployment.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-2-low-unemployment:exam:288f8fe0', 'economics', 'economics:3-2-low-unemployment', '3.2 Low Unemployment', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q19", "question": "Rachel loses her job and receives unemployment benefit. As a result it is most likely that", "options": ["the claimant count measure of unemployment falls", "the claimant count measure of unemployment rises", "the claimant count measure of unemployment is unaffected", "the level of recorded national output will increase"], "hint": "The claimant count counts people receiving unemployment benefit. Rachel has just started receiving it.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: B — the claimant count measure of unemployment rises</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Rachel is now claiming unemployment benefit, so she is added to the claimant count and it rises. Losing a worker would reduce, not increase, national output.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-2-low-unemployment:exam:bfb0fe2b', 'economics', 'economics:3-2-low-unemployment', '3.2 Low Unemployment', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q21", "question": "Unemployment as a result of a long-term change in technology is called", "options": ["cyclical unemployment", "frictional unemployment", "seasonal unemployment", "structural unemployment"], "hint": "A long-term technological change permanently alters which skills are needed — leaving a mismatch.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: D — structural unemployment</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Technology permanently changing an industry leaves workers'' skills mismatched to the jobs available — structural unemployment. It is long-term, not a temporary gap or a seasonal dip.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-2-low-unemployment:exam:fde99355', 'economics', 'economics:3-2-low-unemployment', '3.2 Low Unemployment', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q22", "question": "The unemployment rate is:", "options": ["20%", "25%", "60%", "80%"], "caseStudy": "<p>Plumrith has a population of 1000 of whom 800 people are in the labour force and 200 people are unemployed.</p>", "hint": "Divide by the LABOUR FORCE, not the population. The 1000 is a distractor.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark · Quantitative skills</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: B — 25%</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>200 ÷ 800 × 100 = 25%. Dividing by the population of 1000 gives 20% — the classic trap. The rate is always a share of the labour force.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-2-low-unemployment:exam:d0768319', 'economics', 'economics:3-2-low-unemployment', '3.2 Low Unemployment', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q23", "question": "An increase in the level of unemployment benefit is most likely to", "options": ["increase labour market flexibility", "increase the quantity of labour supplied", "reduce the quantity of labour supplied", "stabilise the level of demand for goods and services"], "hint": "If benefits rise, the gap between not working and working narrows. What does that do to the incentive to take a job?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: C — reduce the quantity of labour supplied</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Higher benefits reduce the financial incentive to take a job, so fewer people offer themselves for work — the supply of labour falls.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-2-low-unemployment:exam:5634aa82', 'economics', 'economics:3-2-low-unemployment', '3.2 Low Unemployment', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q24", "question": "Which of the following is the most likely cost to central government of a high level of unemployment?", "options": ["Encouraging the unemployed to move", "Higher taxes for those in work", "Increased spending on unemployment-related benefits", "Lower living standards for the workforce"], "hint": "The question asks for a cost to CENTRAL GOVERNMENT — money it must pay out. Higher taxes and lower living standards are costs to individuals.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: C — Increased spending on unemployment-related benefits</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>More claimants means the government pays out more in benefits — a direct cost to its budget. Higher taxes and lower living standards fall on individuals, not the government.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-2-low-unemployment:exam:56a9b354', 'economics', 'economics:3-2-low-unemployment', '3.2 Low Unemployment', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q25", "question": "Which of these statements is true about John during the time he was out of work?", "options": ["He was included in the Claimant Count", "He was seasonally unemployed", "He was still part of the workforce", "He was structurally unemployed"], "caseStudy": "<p>John chose to leave his job as a teacher and could not find another job for two months.</p>", "hint": "He is out of work but looking — so he is still able and willing to work. He CHOSE to leave and is between jobs, which is frictional, and we aren''t told he claimed anything.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: C — He was still part of the workforce</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>John is available for and seeking work, so he remains in the workforce. His is frictional, not seasonal or structural, unemployment — and we are not told he claimed JSA, so A cannot be assumed.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-2-low-unemployment:exam:54e68a5f', 'economics', 'economics:3-2-low-unemployment', '3.2 Low Unemployment', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q26", "question": "Most coal mines in the UK have closed down. What type of unemployment has this caused?", "options": ["Cyclical", "Frictional", "Seasonal", "Structural"], "hint": "The industry has permanently gone — miners'' skills no longer match available vacancies.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: D — Structural</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>The permanent decline of the coal industry leaves miners with skills that do not match the jobs available — structural unemployment.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-2-low-unemployment:exam:f768b6a2', 'economics', 'economics:3-2-low-unemployment', '3.2 Low Unemployment', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q27", "question": "The table gives data for two countries. Which of the following statements about the claimant count measure of unemployment is correct?", "options": ["It cannot be calculated without further information", "It is higher in country Y than in country Z", "It is higher in country Z than in country Y", "It is the same in both countries"], "caseStudy": "<table style=\"width:100%;max-width:520px;margin:12px auto;border-collapse:collapse;text-align:left;font-size:14px;\">\n<tr style=\"border-bottom:1px solid var(--border);\"><th style=\"padding:6px;\">Country</th><th style=\"padding:6px;\">Population</th><th style=\"padding:6px;\">Workforce</th><th style=\"padding:6px;\">Unemployed and claiming benefits</th></tr>\n<tr><td style=\"padding:6px;\">Y</td><td style=\"padding:6px;\">150000</td><td style=\"padding:6px;\">100000</td><td style=\"padding:6px;\">10000</td></tr>\n<tr><td style=\"padding:6px;\">Z</td><td style=\"padding:6px;\">250000</td><td style=\"padding:6px;\">200000</td><td style=\"padding:6px;\">20000</td></tr>\n</table>", "hint": "Work out claimants ÷ workforce × 100 for each country. Z has twice the claimants but also twice the workforce.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark · Quantitative skills</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: D — It is the same in both countries</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Y: 10,000 ÷ 100,000 × 100 = 10%. Z: 20,000 ÷ 200,000 × 100 = 10%. Z has more claimants in absolute terms but the same RATE, because its workforce is twice as large.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-2-low-unemployment:mcq:61bf0dba', 'economics', 'economics:3-2-low-unemployment', '3.2 Low Unemployment', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "In economics, an unemployed person is someone who...", "options": ["Has chosen to stop working", "Is too young or too old to work", "Is willing and able to work at current wage rates but cannot find a job", "Does not have a paid job for any reason"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "Unemployment requires being willing AND able to work but unable to find a job. People not seeking work are economically inactive, not unemployed."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-2-low-unemployment:mcq:cfce98e9', 'economics', 'economics:3-2-low-unemployment', '3.2 Low Unemployment', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "The claimant count measures unemployment by counting people who...", "options": ["Receive unemployment benefits such as Jobseeker''s Allowance", "Are surveyed by the Labour Force Survey", "Do not have a job at all", "Are looking for any kind of job"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "It counts benefit claimants only, so it misses people who are out of work and looking but not entitled to claim — which is why the LFS gives a higher figure."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-2-low-unemployment:mcq:265888fb', 'economics', 'economics:3-2-low-unemployment', '3.2 Low Unemployment', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Why is the Labour Force Survey better for comparing unemployment between countries?", "options": ["It only counts benefit claimants", "It is published more often", "It always gives a lower figure", "It uses a standardised international methodology"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "explain": "The LFS asks a standard question of a household sample using an internationally agreed method, so the figures are comparable across countries."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-2-low-unemployment:mcq:c964a30a', 'economics', 'economics:3-2-low-unemployment', '3.2 Low Unemployment', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "A country has 1 million unemployed and a workforce of 10 million. Its unemployment rate is...", "options": ["100%", "10%", "0.1%", "1%"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "1m ÷ 10m × 100 = 10%. Note another country with the same LEVEL (1m unemployed) but a 50m workforce would have a rate of only 2% — which is why the rate matters more."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-2-low-unemployment:mcq:9dcd6826', 'economics', 'economics:3-2-low-unemployment', '3.2 Low Unemployment', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Jane sells ice creams at a seaside resort in summer and is out of work the rest of the year. This is...", "options": ["Seasonal unemployment", "Frictional unemployment", "Structural unemployment", "Cyclical unemployment"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Her job only exists at a certain time of year — seasonal unemployment, caused by a fall in demand during a particular season."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-2-low-unemployment:mcq:02ff6bd9', 'economics', 'economics:3-2-low-unemployment', '3.2 Low Unemployment', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which type of unemployment is generally considered healthy for an economy?", "options": ["Cyclical", "Seasonal", "Structural", "Frictional"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "explain": "Frictional unemployment is the short gap between jobs, and it shows workers moving from less productive roles into more productive ones."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-2-low-unemployment:mcq:7837d2c3', 'economics', 'economics:3-2-low-unemployment', '3.2 Low Unemployment', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "The permanent closure of the UK''s coal mines caused which type of unemployment?", "options": ["Frictional", "Structural", "Seasonal", "Cyclical"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "A permanent decline in an industry leaves workers whose skills no longer match available vacancies — structural unemployment."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-2-low-unemployment:mcq:1adb5628', 'economics', 'economics:3-2-low-unemployment', '3.2 Low Unemployment', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which is most likely to reduce unemployment?", "options": ["Increased government expenditure", "Increased imports", "Increased taxes", "Increased interest rates"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "More government spending raises total demand, so firms produce more and hire more workers. The other three reduce demand for domestic output."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-2-low-unemployment:mcq:1acc8746', 'economics', 'economics:3-2-low-unemployment', '3.2 Low Unemployment', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Unemployment rises. What happens to the government''s budget?", "options": ["Nothing changes", "Tax revenue falls and benefit spending rises, widening the deficit", "Tax revenue rises and benefit spending falls", "Both tax revenue and spending fall"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "The ''double hit'': fewer earners means less income tax and VAT, while more claimants means more benefit spending — so the deficit widens."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-2-low-unemployment:mcq:cc9a2243', 'economics', 'economics:3-2-low-unemployment', '3.2 Low Unemployment', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "An increase in the level of unemployment benefit is most likely to...", "options": ["Have no effect on the labour market", "Increase labour market flexibility", "Increase the quantity of labour supplied", "Reduce the quantity of labour supplied"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "explain": "Higher benefits narrow the gap between working and not working, reducing the financial incentive to take a job — so fewer people offer themselves for work."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-2-low-unemployment:tf:38e1708f', 'economics', 'economics:3-2-low-unemployment', '3.2 Low Unemployment', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "Anyone without a paid job is counted as unemployed."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "Only those willing AND able to work but unable to find a job. Students, carers and pensioners not seeking work are economically inactive, not unemployed."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-2-low-unemployment:tf:e0c77c53', 'economics', 'economics:3-2-low-unemployment', '3.2 Low Unemployment', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "The unemployment rate is calculated as a percentage of the total population."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "It is a percentage of the WORKFORCE. Dividing by the population is the classic exam trap — Plumrith''s 200 unemployed out of 800 in the labour force is 25%, not 20%."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-2-low-unemployment:tf:be1d229b', 'economics', 'economics:3-2-low-unemployment', '3.2 Low Unemployment', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "The Labour Force Survey usually gives a higher figure than the claimant count."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "The LFS captures people who are out of work and looking but not entitled to claim benefits, so it counts more people than the claimant count does."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-2-low-unemployment:tf:c3a0da28', 'economics', 'economics:3-2-low-unemployment', '3.2 Low Unemployment', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "Frictional unemployment is generally seen as healthy for an economy."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "It is the short gap between jobs and shows workers moving from less productive roles into more productive ones."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-2-low-unemployment:tf:6ce20ef3', 'economics', 'economics:3-2-low-unemployment', '3.2 Low Unemployment', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "Two countries with the same level of unemployment must have the same unemployment rate."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "1 million unemployed is 2% of a 50m workforce but 10% of a 10m workforce. Same level, very different rate — which is why the rate is the more useful measure."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-2-low-unemployment:tf:f8a110db', 'economics', 'economics:3-2-low-unemployment', '3.2 Low Unemployment', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "When unemployment falls, the government''s budget deficit is likely to shrink."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "More workers means more income tax, NI and VAT revenue, while fewer claimants means less benefit spending — both improve the budget together."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-2-low-unemployment:tf:9788bdd3', 'economics', 'economics:3-2-low-unemployment', '3.2 Low Unemployment', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "High unemployment in a region means employers there have fewer workers available."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "The opposite — high unemployment means a SURPLUS of labour, so employers can recruit more easily and at lower wages. A real exemplar lost marks on this false logic."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-2-low-unemployment:tf:41eddf96', 'economics', 'economics:3-2-low-unemployment', '3.2 Low Unemployment', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "Cyclical unemployment is caused by a fall in demand across the economy."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "Lower demand means less output is needed, so fewer workers are needed — and the resulting fall in household spending can push demand down further."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-2-low-unemployment:learn:48703c1c', 'economics', 'economics:3-2-low-unemployment', '3.2 Low Unemployment', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Employment, unemployment and how it is measured", "reading": "<p><strong>Employment</strong> is the use of labour to produce goods and services. <strong>Unemployment</strong> is NOT simply \"not having a job\" — in economics it means someone who is <strong>willing and able to work</strong> at current wage rates but <strong>cannot find a job</strong>.</p>\n<h4>Why the definition matters</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>A stay-at-home parent, a retired pensioner and a full-time student are not unemployed — they are <strong>economically inactive</strong>, because they are not able and willing to work.</li>\n<li>A graduate who has just left university and is looking for work IS unemployed — a real exam MCQ.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Two ways the UK measures it</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Claimant count</strong> — the number of people <strong>receiving unemployment benefits</strong> (Jobseeker''s Allowance). Simple, but it misses anyone out of work and looking who is not entitled to claim.</li>\n<li><strong>Labour Force Survey (LFS)</strong> — contacts a sample of households and asks whether anyone is willing and able to work but cannot find a job. It generally gives a <strong>higher</strong> figure than the claimant count, and because it uses a standardised international methodology it is the best measure for <strong>comparing countries</strong>.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Level vs rate — the crucial distinction</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Level</strong> = the total NUMBER of people unemployed. <strong>Rate</strong> = the PERCENTAGE of the workforce that is unemployed.</li>\n<li>Country A: 1 million unemployed from a 50 million workforce = <strong>2%</strong>. Country B: 1 million unemployed from a 10 million workforce = <strong>10%</strong>. Same level, wildly different rate — which is why the RATE is far more meaningful.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "Which of these people counts as unemployed?", "options": ["A young adult who has just left university and is looking for a job", "A full-time student who sometimes works in a café", "A father who chooses to stay at home to look after a child", "A pensioner who is looking for part-time work"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Unemployed = of working age, without work, and willing and able to work. The stay-at-home father is inactive by choice, the pensioner is beyond working age, and the student already has some work."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-2-low-unemployment:learn:14d7c347', 'economics', 'economics:3-2-low-unemployment', '3.2 Low Unemployment', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Calculating the rate and reading the data", "reading": "<p>Every 3.2 paper contains a rate calculation and a data question. Both are easy marks — and both have a trap that catches candidates every year.</p>\n<h4>The formula</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Unemployment rate (%) = (number unemployed ÷ total workforce) × 100</strong></li>\n<li><strong>The denominator is the WORKFORCE</strong> — never the population. Plumrith has 1,000 people but only 800 in the labour force, so 200 unemployed is 200 ÷ 800 = <strong>25%</strong>, not 20%. Papers deliberately give you a population figure and an under-18 figure as distractors.</li>\n<li><strong>Always write the % sign.</strong> The mark scheme docks a mark without it — an easy mark thrown away.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Worked examples from the real papers</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Northern Ireland: 26 ÷ 877 × 100 = <strong>2.96%</strong>.</li>\n<li>2 million unemployed from a 35 million working population: 2 ÷ 35 × 100 = <strong>5.71%</strong>.</li>\n<li>2.52m unemployed from a 31.5m workforce = <strong>8.0%</strong> (ignore the 52.5m population and the 8.5m under-18s).</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Reading unemployment trends</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Rising</strong> unemployment signals a slowing economy; staying <strong>high</strong> for a long period suggests a <strong>recession</strong>.</li>\n<li><strong>Falling</strong> unemployment suggests a growing economy; staying <strong>very low</strong> for a long period may suggest a <strong>boom</strong>.</li>\n<li><strong>Explain, don''t describe.</strong> \"Unemployment rose between 2008 and 2011\" is only half the answer — you must add WHY (the financial crisis cut demand, so firms laid workers off).</li>\n</ul>", "question": "A town has a population of 1,000, a labour force of 800, and 200 unemployed. The unemployment rate is...", "options": ["25%", "60%", "20%", "80%"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "200 ÷ 800 × 100 = 25%. Dividing by the population (1,000) gives 20% — the classic trap. Always divide by the WORKFORCE."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-2-low-unemployment:learn:84302da8', 'economics', 'economics:3-2-low-unemployment', '3.2 Low Unemployment', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "The four types of unemployment", "reading": "<p>Naming the type is worth marks — but the exam wants the <strong>cause</strong> too. Learn each as a matched pair.</p>\n<h4>1. Seasonal — jobs that only exist at certain times of year</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Theme parks close over winter; ski resorts only run in winter; harvesting needs extra workers only at harvest. Devon and Cornwall see this heavily out of the tourist season.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>2. Frictional — the temporary gap between jobs</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Caused by <strong>time lags</strong> as workers move from one job to the next. It is considered <strong>healthy</strong>: it shows workers moving from less productive roles into more productive ones.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>3. Structural — an industry permanently declines</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>The mark scheme needs BOTH halves:</strong> an industry declines AND that leaves a <strong>mismatch</strong> between workers'' skills and the vacancies available. Omitting the mismatch is the commonest error.</li>\n<li>Workers lack <strong>transferable skills</strong> and are often <strong>geographically immobile</strong> — family ties, or property worth too little to fund a move.</li>\n<li><strong>The vicious cycle:</strong> industry declines → local unemployment rises → less local spending → other local firms collapse → those who can, leave → the area becomes deprived → property values fall further.</li>\n<li>UK examples: the North of England and the Welsh valleys after the mining decline of the late 1980s — both still show higher unemployment today.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>4. Cyclical — a fall in demand across the economy</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Lower demand → less output needed → fewer workers needed. It has its own vicious circle: more unemployment → less household spending → demand falls further → more lay-offs.</li>\n<li>This is the type the government can fight with expansionary fiscal policy.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Real situations often combine types.</strong> Blackpool suffers <em>seasonal</em> (summer visitors), <em>cyclical</em> (holidays are the first thing households cut in a downturn) and arguably <em>structural</em> unemployment (holidaymakers switched to the Mediterranean).</p>", "question": "For full marks, explaining structural unemployment needs an industry declining AND...", "options": ["A mismatch between workers'' skills and the available vacancies", "Jobs only existing in certain seasons", "A fall in demand across the whole economy", "Workers waiting to start a new job"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Both halves are needed. The examiners noted several candidates omitted the MISMATCH of skills — which is what makes structural unemployment so long-lasting."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-2-low-unemployment:learn:0458bfb2', 'economics', 'economics:3-2-low-unemployment', '3.2 Low Unemployment', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Consequences of unemployment — individuals, regions, government", "reading": "<p>The spec asks you to evaluate consequences for three groups. Know each, and know that unemployment even has some benefits.</p>\n<h4>For individuals</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Lower income and living standards</strong> — benefits pay less than a job.</li>\n<li><strong>Personal and social strain</strong> — loss of status and self-esteem, problems within families.</li>\n<li><strong>\"Excluded workers\"</strong> — employers want recent experience, so the long-term unemployed may stop applying altogether and drop out of the workforce.</li>\n<li>Those still IN work pay too: higher taxes/National Insurance to fund benefits, and heavier workloads causing stress.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>For regions</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Persistent unemployment creates <strong>depressed areas</strong>: local businesses fail, causing more unemployment; those who can afford to leave do so; house prices fall; crime rates tend to rise.</li>\n<li>Regional data proves it — the North East has 4.22% unemployment vs England''s 3.63%, and 25.2% economically inactive vs 21.2%.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>For government — the \"double hit\"</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>1. Tax revenue falls</strong> (fewer people earning, so less income tax and NI; less spending, so less VAT).</li>\n<li><strong>2. Spending rises</strong> (more claimants for unemployment benefits).</li>\n<li>Both at once make a <strong>budget deficit</strong> and more borrowing likely. Spending on benefits also has an <strong>opportunity cost</strong> — that money cannot fund schools or hospitals.</li>\n<li><strong>Use the right words:</strong> a smaller/larger <strong>deficit</strong> or a move toward <strong>surplus</strong> — never a \"bigger\" or \"smaller\" budget.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>The benefits (worth an evaluation mark)</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Frictional unemployment moves workers into more productive industries.</li>\n<li>High unemployment means more competition for each job, which <strong>keeps wages low</strong> — cutting firms'' costs, making them more internationally competitive and potentially boosting exports.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "Why is unemployment a ''double hit'' to the government''s budget?", "options": ["It raises both inflation and interest rates", "It raises wages and prices together", "Tax revenue falls AND benefit spending rises at the same time", "It cuts both exports and imports"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "Fewer earners means less income tax and VAT, while more claimants means more benefit spending. Both sides of the budget worsen together, making a deficit more likely."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-2-low-unemployment:misc:66c7f353', 'economics', 'economics:3-2-low-unemployment', '3.2 Low Unemployment', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> \"Unemployment rose between 2008 and 2011. That answers the question.\"</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> This is the flagged Misconception on the real paper. The examiners wrote that although the vast majority of candidates correctly recognised unemployment had increased, many DESCRIBED the trend rather than EXPLAINING it — and the question said ''explain''. Stating the direction earns 1 mark; the second mark needs a REASON. Here: the global financial crisis caused a recession, so total demand fell, firms had fewer orders and laid workers off, leaving fewer vacancies. The habit generalises — whenever a question says ''explain the trend'', give direction + cause, never direction alone.</p>", "question": "''Explain the trend in unemployment between 2008 and 2011.'' What earns the second mark?", "options": ["Saying it rose sharply rather than just rose", "Quoting more figures from the chart", "A reason — e.g. the financial crisis cut demand so firms laid workers off", "Describing the shape of the line"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "Direction alone is 1 mark. The examiners were explicit: many described rather than explained. The reason is what earns the second mark."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-2-low-unemployment:misc:7918119e', 'economics', 'economics:3-2-low-unemployment', '3.2 Low Unemployment', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> \"Lower unemployment means the government''s budget gets smaller.\"</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> The Assessment for Learning note on this paper singles this out: a significant number of candidates wrote about the budget becoming ''bigger or smaller'', rather than using the correct terms. The budget is the DIFFERENCE between spending and tax revenue, so it isn''t ''big'' or ''small'' — it is in DEFICIT (spending exceeds revenue) or SURPLUS (revenue exceeds spending). When unemployment falls, revenue rises and benefit spending falls, so the correct phrasing is: a SMALLER DEFICIT, a move NEARER TO BALANCE, or a LARGER SURPLUS. Using the right vocabulary is what separates a Level 3 answer here.</p>", "question": "Unemployment falls, so tax revenue rises and benefit spending falls. The correct way to describe the budget effect is...", "options": ["The budget gets smaller", "The budget gets bigger", "A smaller deficit / a move towards surplus", "The budget disappears"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "The budget is the difference between spending and revenue, so it moves between deficit and surplus. ''Bigger/smaller budget'' was explicitly flagged as the wrong terminology."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-2-low-unemployment:misc:218ad93b', 'economics', 'economics:3-2-low-unemployment', '3.2 Low Unemployment', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> \"To explain how unemployment affected the budget, I''ll describe how the government used fiscal policy to cut unemployment.\"</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> This is a Misconception the examiners named directly: a reasonable number of candidates misunderstood the question and wrote about how the government ACHIEVED lower unemployment through expansionary fiscal policy. That was not what the question asked. The question runs the other way — unemployment CHANGED (for its own reasons), and you must trace what that change DID to the budget. Direction of causation matters: read whether the policy is the cause or the consequence before you start writing.</p>", "question": "''Analyse how changes in unemployment affected the government''s budget'' is asking you to...", "options": ["Describe the level of unemployment", "Trace what the unemployment change did to tax revenue and spending", "Evaluate whether the policy worked", "Explain how fiscal policy reduced unemployment"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "Unemployment is the CAUSE and the budget is the effect. Writing about fiscal policy reducing unemployment reverses the causation and scores nothing."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-2-low-unemployment:misc:b03a03ff', 'economics', 'economics:3-2-low-unemployment', '3.2 Low Unemployment', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> \"The North East has high unemployment, so producers there struggle to find workers.\"</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> This is false logic, and the examiners published an exemplar showing exactly it. High unemployment means MORE workers are available, not fewer — the supply of labour exceeds demand for it. That is why one of the credited BENEFITS for North East producers is that they can recruit at lower wage rates, cutting costs and raising profits. The genuine costs run elsewhere: a depressed local economy means less demand and lower revenue, and long-term unemployed workers need retraining, which raises costs. Get the direction right before you evaluate — evaluating a false premise earns nothing.</p>", "question": "High regional unemployment means producers there face...", "options": ["A surplus of labour, so they can pay lower wages", "Higher productivity automatically", "A shortage of workers, so they must pay more", "No change to their wage costs"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "High unemployment = labour supply exceeds demand = lower wages. The exemplar that claimed ''fewer workers available'' was evaluating false logic and scored nothing."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-2-low-unemployment:misc:8372f584', 'economics', 'economics:3-2-low-unemployment', '3.2 Low Unemployment', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> \"200 unemployed in a town of 1,000 people — that''s a 20% unemployment rate.\"</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> The denominator is always the WORKFORCE (labour force), never the population. Plumrith has 1,000 people but only 800 in the labour force, so the rate is 200 ÷ 800 × 100 = 25%. Papers deliberately hand you distractors: one question gives a population of 52.5 million AND 8.5 million under-18s, but the answer uses only the 31.5 million workforce (2.52 ÷ 31.5 = 8.0%). The same discipline applies to the £ and % signs — the mark scheme docks a mark for a bare number, so 2 ÷ 35 × 100 must be written as 5.71%, not 5.71.</p>", "question": "Population 52.5m, under-18s 8.5m, workforce 31.5m, unemployed 2.52m. The unemployment rate is...", "options": ["8.0%", "6.3%", "4.8%", "5.7%"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "2.52 ÷ 31.5 × 100 = 8.0%. The population and under-18 figures are deliberate distractors — always divide by the workforce."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-2-low-unemployment:tips:7287a2b3', 'economics', 'economics:3-2-low-unemployment', '3.2 Low Unemployment', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "definition — Definitions: the precise words that earn the second mark", "reading": "<p>The short questions are free marks IF you use the technical vocabulary. Real examples from this paper:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Unemployment rate</strong> = \"the percentage of the country''s WORKFORCE that is unemployed\". Examiners noted candidates who said ''population'' instead of workforce lost the precision mark.</li>\n<li><strong>Structural unemployment</strong> = an industry declining AND a MISMATCH between skills and vacancies. Several candidates omitted the mismatch — the very thing that defines it.</li>\n<li><strong>Fiscal policy</strong> = government TAXATION (1) and government SPENDING (1). Name both.</li>\n<li><strong>Imports</strong> = goods AND services bought from abroad, with an outflow of money. Saying only \"a good from another country\" caps you at 1.</li>\n<li><strong>Explain one type of unemployment</strong> = name the type AND its cause, e.g. \"cyclical is caused by a lack of demand\".</li>\n</ul>", "question": "Which definition of the unemployment rate earns both marks?", "options": ["The people claiming benefits", "The number of people without a job", "The percentage of the country''s workforce that is unemployed", "The percentage of the population without work"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "''Workforce'' is the technical term examiners wanted, and it must be a percentage. ''Population'' and bare ''level'' definitions lost marks."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-2-low-unemployment:tips:cd2e943b', 'economics', 'economics:3-2-low-unemployment', '3.2 Low Unemployment', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "calculation — Calculations: workforce denominator, and the % sign", "reading": "<p>Two rules cover every calculation on this topic:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Divide by the WORKFORCE</strong>, never the population. 200 ÷ 800 = 25% (not 200 ÷ 1000 = 20%). 2.52m ÷ 31.5m = 8.0% (ignore the 52.5m population).</li>\n<li><strong>Include the % sign.</strong> \"Give 1 mark if the % sign is omitted\" appears in the mark scheme. The examiners'' own tip: \"make sure they include a % sign in percentage answers\".</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>The worked ones</h4>\n<p>Northern Ireland: 26 ÷ 877 × 100 = 2.96%. A 35m working population with 2m unemployed: 5.71%. Port Talbot''s average: (8.9 + 6.9 + 6.9) ÷ 3 = 7.6% — use only the Port Talbot row, and round as instructed.</p>", "question": "Northern Ireland has 877 thousand economically active and 26 thousand unemployed. The rate is...", "options": ["2.96%", "3.38%", "26%", "2.96"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "26 ÷ 877 × 100 = 2.96%. Without the % sign it is capped at 1 mark — the examiners flagged this exact omission."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-2-low-unemployment:tips:82dc1bc0', 'economics', 'economics:3-2-low-unemployment', '3.2 Low Unemployment', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "analysis — Analyse the budget: run BOTH chains, then name the effect", "reading": "<p>This 6-marker appears twice on this paper. The examiners said the best answers reasoned <strong>both</strong> sides and then stated the budget effect.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Start with the definition</strong>: the budget is the difference between government spending and tax revenue.</li>\n<li><strong>Use the DIRECTION from the extract</strong> — unemployment falling 2011–2017, rising 2005–2011. The examiners called this \"a key to this question\".</li>\n<li><strong>Chain 1 (revenue)</strong>: more people in work → more income tax and NI → they spend more → more VAT.</li>\n<li><strong>Chain 2 (spending)</strong>: fewer claimants → less spent on JSA/unemployment benefits.</li>\n<li><strong>Then the effect, in the right words</strong>: a smaller DEFICIT / nearer to balance / a larger SURPLUS.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "What did examiners say the BEST budget answers did?", "options": ["Explained how fiscal policy cuts unemployment", "Quoted the most data", "Reasoned both tax revenue AND spending, then showed the effect on the budget", "Focused only on benefit spending"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "Both chains plus the overall budget effect. Some candidates just stated the outcome without analysing why; others reversed the causation and wrote about fiscal policy."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-2-low-unemployment:tips:0ead71f3', 'economics', 'economics:3-2-low-unemployment', '3.2 Low Unemployment', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "evaluate — Evaluate: match the points and reach a judgement", "reading": "<p>The examiners were direct: evaluative skill is <strong>NOT</strong> demonstrated by writing a good point and then a bad point.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Use the case data</strong> — \"better answers effectively used the data in the case study to emphasise their points\" (North East: 4.2% &gt; 3.6%; inactive 25.2% &gt; 21.2%).</li>\n<li><strong>Answer for the right group.</strong> \"Consequences for PRODUCERS\" is about costs, revenue and wages — not about how the workers feel.</li>\n<li><strong>Check your logic before evaluating it.</strong> The published exemplar evaluated a false premise (high unemployment = fewer workers) and earned nothing.</li>\n<li><strong>Always finish with a judgement</strong> — that exemplar also had no conclusion at all.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>The best evaluation lever on this topic</h4>\n<p>Almost every \"consequences of unemployment\" question turns on <strong>the TYPE of unemployment</strong>: someone frictionally unemployed finds work again quickly and suffers little; someone structurally unemployed may never regain similar work. It also depends on how generous benefits are.</p>", "question": "For ''evaluate the consequences of unemployment for individuals'', the strongest evaluative lever is...", "options": ["It depends on the TYPE — frictional is brief, structural can be permanent", "Saying unemployment is always bad", "Listing three costs then three benefits", "Repeating the extract''s figures"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "The mark scheme names the type of unemployment (and the level of benefits) as the key evaluation. A list of good/bad points is not evaluation."}'::jsonb)
